'''Marcus Lilian Thuram-Ulien''' ({{IPA|fr|maʁkys tyʁam}};<ref>{{cite web |date=17 November 2022 |title=Dans la chambre de Marcus Thuram, Equipe de France {{!}} FFF 2022 |trans-title=In the room of Marcus Thuram, French {{!}} FFF 2022 team |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NJK091AXAMA |access-date=1 September 2023 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=[[French Football Federation]] |language=fr}}</ref> born 6 August 1997) is a French professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Serie A]] club [[Inter Milan]] and the [[France national football team|France national team]].

Thuram began his professional career at [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]] in 2015, where he played in three [[Ligue 2]] seasons, before moving to [[En Avant Guingamp|Guingamp]] in 2017, spending two years in [[Ligue 1]]. He then joined [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]], spending four seasons in Germany, before signing for Inter Milan as a free agent in 2023, and winning the [[2023–24 Serie A|Serie A title]] in his first season.

Thuram made his senior international debut for France in 2020 and was part of their squads at the [[UEFA European Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]], and the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], finishing as runner-up at the latter.

==Club career==
===Sochaux===
Thuram started his professional career at [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]], where he also played for the club's youth team. He made his [[Ligue 2]] debut on 20 March 2015 against [[LB Châteauroux|Châteauroux]], replacing [[Edouard Butin]] on 83 minutes.<ref name="soccerway2">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/03/20/france/ligue-2/fc-sochaux-montbeliard/la-berrichonne-chateauroux/1688015/|title=FC Sochaux vs. Châteauroux - 20 March 2015 - Soccerway|publisher=soccerway.com|access-date=16 April 2014}}</ref> He played 43 total matches for Sochaux and scored one goal, in a 3–1 loss at [[Tours FC|Tours]] on 14 April 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sochaux encore à côté de la plaque… |url=https://www.estrepublicain.fr/sport-franc-comtois/2017/04/15/sochaux-encore-a-cote-de-la-plaque |access-date=27 December 2018 |work=Est-Republicain |date=15 April 2017|trans-title=Sochaux off the mark again…}}</ref>

===Guingamp===
On 5 July 2017, Thuram joined [[Ligue 1]] club [[En Avant Guingamp|Guingamp]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marcus Thuram, c'est fait ! |url=https://www.letelegramme.fr/football/guingamp-marcus-thuram-c-est-fait-05-07-2017-11585194.php |access-date=27 December 2018 |work=Le Télégramme |date=5 July 2017|trans-title=Marcus Thuram, it's a done deal!}}</ref> In August 2018, he gained attention for playing against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon]], a long-term teammate of his father at Parma and [[Juventus FC|Juventus]].<ref name=bbc/>

Thuram scored an added-time penalty on 9 January 2019 to eliminate holders PSG from the quarter-finals of the [[Coupe de la Ligue]], having earlier missed from the spot in the 2–1 win at the [[Parc des Princes]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lermusieaux |first1=Jocelyn |title=PSG-Guingamp : Marcus Thuram a eu du cran pour tirer son deuxième penalty |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Article/Pour-tirer-le-troisieme-penalty-marcus-thuram-a-eu-du-cran/975846 |access-date=21 February 2019 |work=L'Équipe |date=10 January 2019 |language=fr|trans-title=PSG-Guingamp: Marcus Thuram had the guts to take his second penalty}}</ref> Twenty days later he scored the equaliser in a 2–2 home draw with [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in the semi-final, and his attempt in the subsequent penalty shootout was saved by [[Danijel Subašić]] though Guingamp nonetheless advanced.<ref>{{cite news |title=Monaco lose on penalties at Guingamp in Jardim's 1st match |url=https://www.apnews.com/c6ae8df619a448abb7ac239e60d56d56 |access-date=21 February 2019 |publisher=Associated Press |date=29 January 2019}}</ref>

===Borussia Mönchengladbach===
====2019–20: Debut season====
On 22 July 2019, [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] announced they had signed Thuram on a four-year deal. The transfer fee paid to Guingamp was reported as €12 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Transferts-marcus-thuram-guingamp-s-engage-avec-monchengladbach-officiel/1042542|title=Transferts : Marcus Thuram (Guingamp) s'engage avec Mönchengladbach (officiel)|date=22 July 2019|access-date=22 July 2019|publisher=[[L'Équipe]]|trans-title=Transfers: Marcus Thuram (Guingamp) signs with Mönchengladbach (official)}}</ref> He was given the number 10 shirt, vacated by [[Thorgan Hazard]] after his move to [[Borussia Dortmund]]. He made his debut for ''Gladbach'' on 9 August in the first round of the [[DFB-Pokal]] away to [[2. Bundesliga]] club [[SV Sandhausen]], and scored the only goal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Borussia battle to DFB-Pokal second round |url=https://www.borussia.de/english/team/news/borussia-news/news-detailansicht.html |access-date=30 September 2019 |publisher=Borussia Mönchengladbach |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> He got his first [[Bundesliga]] goals on his fifth appearance on 22 September, scoring both of a 2–1 home win over [[Fortuna Düsseldorf]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brassell |first=Andy |date=2019-09-23 |title=Marcus Thuram's derby double lifts Gladbach from European humiliation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/sep/23/marcus-thuram-bundesliga-gladbach-dusseldorf |access-date=2026-04-21 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

On 31 May 2020, Thuram scored twice in a 4–1 win over [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]]. He took a knee after his first goal of the match and dedicated the strike in honour of ongoing protests in the United States following the [[murder of George Floyd]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/borussia-monchengladbach/story/4104282/gladbachs-marcus-thuram-dedicates-goal-to-us-protests|title=Gladbach's Marcus Thuram dedicates goal to U.S. protests|website=ESPN|date=31 May 2020|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref>

====2021–2023: Later seasons and Champions League qualification====

On 27 October 2020, Thuram scored twice in a 2–2 draw with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the group stage of the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group B|UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=History: Mönchengladbach 2-2 Real Madrid: UEFA Champions League 2020/21 Group stage |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2029400--monchengladbach-vs-real-madrid/ |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=UEFA.com |language=en}}</ref> On 19 December, Thuram was sent off for spitting in the face of opponent [[Stefan Posch]] as Gladbach fell to a 2–1 defeat to [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fahey |first=James Ellingworth ciaran |date=2020-12-19 |title=Gladbach's Marcus Thuram spits in opponent's face |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/gladbachs-thuram-sent-off-for-spitting-in-opponents-face/ |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=The Seattle Times |language=en-US}}</ref> and was given a six-match ban and a €40,000 fine.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |date=2020-12-21 |title=Gladbach's Marcus Thuram handed six-match ban for spitting at opponent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/dec/21/marcus-thuram-handed-six-match-ban-for-spitting-at-opponent-borussia-monchengladbach |access-date=2026-04-21 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Thuram failed to score in his first 15 Bundesliga matches of the [[2021–22 Bundesliga]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Danny |first=Owen |date=2022-02-14 |title=No goals, no assists: £21m striker in nightmare season after Spurs talks |url=https://www.hitc.com/no-goals-no-assists-21m-striker-in-nightmare-season-after-spurs-talks/ |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=www.hitc.com |language=en-GB}}</ref> He later scored only three goals, one each against [[VfL Wolfsburg|Wolfsburg]], [[VfB Stuttgart|Stuttgart]] and [[SpVgg Greuther Fürth|Greuther Fürth]]. As of November 2022, Thuram managed to score 10 goals in 15 [[2022–23 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] matches, in which he equaled his personal best since the debut season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Thuram thriving in Farke's quiet revolution |url=https://www.dw.com/en/marcus-thuram-thriving-in-daniel-farkes-quiet-gladbach-revolution/a-63453161 |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dániel |first=Gazdag |date=2022-02-14 |title=181bet |url=https://181bet1.net/ |access-date=2026-04-21 |language=en-GB}}</ref> In April 2023, Gladbach's [[sporting director]] Roland Virkus confirmed that Thuram would depart the club at the end of the 2022–23 campaign, having chosen not to renew his contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 April 2023 |title=Virkus: "Für eine neue Struktur braucht es einen stabilen Rahmen" |url=https://www.borussia.de/de/aktuelles/news/2023-04-13-virkus-fuer-eine-neue-struktur-braucht-es-einen-stabilen-rahmen |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=Borussia Mönchengladbach |language=de-DE|trans-title=Virkus: "A new structure requires a stable framework"}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Borussia bestätigt: Auch Thuram und Bensebaini sind im Sommer weg |trans-title=Borussia confirms: Thuram and Bensebaini are also leaving in the summer |url=https://www.kicker.de/borussia-bestaetigt-auch-thuram-und-bensebaini-sind-im-sommer-weg-946596/artikel |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=kicker |language=de-DE}}</ref>

===Inter Milan===
On 1 July 2023, Thuram was officially signed as a free agent by the [[Serie A]] team, [[Inter Milan]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Marcus Thuram signs for Inter {{!}} Inter.it |url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/marcus-thuram-signs-for-inter |access-date=2023-07-01 |website=www.inter.it |language=en}}</ref> His contract with the club is set to last until June 2028.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |date=2023-07-01 |title=Inter Milan sign French forward Thuram from Monchengladbach |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/inter-milan-sign-french-forward-thuram-monchengladbach-2023-07-01/ |access-date=2023-07-01}}</ref> On 3 September, he scored his first goal in a 4–0 win over [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://football-italia.net/serie-a-inter-4-0-fiorentina-total-domination/ |title=Serie A {{!}} Inter 4-0 Fiorentina: Total domination |publisher=Football Italia |date=3 September 2023 }}</ref> On 3 October, he scored his first [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] goal for the club in a 1–0 victory over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the group stage,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/thuram-martinez-inter-benfica-champions-league-a0b3db4252e3993444c5525f7873e160 |title=Thuram scores to help Inter beat Benfica 1-0 and go joint top of Champions League group |publisher=AP News |date=3 October 2023 }}</ref> becoming the third Frenchman to score in this competition for Inter after [[Youri Djorkaeff]] (1998 vs [[Sturm Graz]]) and [[Patrick Vieira]] (2006 vs [[Bayern Munich]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sempreinter.com/2023/10/04/marcus-thuram-becomes-third-french-inter-milan-player-score-champions-league/|title=Photo – Marcus Thuram Becomes Third French Inter Milan Player To Score In Champions League – Joins Arsenal Legend & 1998 FIFA World Cup Winner|website=Sempre Inter|date=3 October 2023|access-date=9 October 2023}}</ref> He scored 13 goals and added an equal number of assists as Inter won the league in his first season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Campanale |first1=Susy |title=Video: Thuram father and son celebrate Serie A title |url=https://football-italia.net/video-thuram-father-and-son-celebrate-serie-a/ |access-date=17 June 2024 |publisher=Football Italia |date=19 May 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
Thuram was a member of [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] which won the [[2016 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2016 UEFA European Championship]]. In November 2020, he was called up for the first time to the [[France national football team|senior team]], ahead of games against [[Finland national football team|Finland]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] and [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bacon |first1=Jake |title=Borussia Monchengladbach star Marcus Thuram receives first senior France call-up… 12 years after dad Lilian retired |url=https://talksport.com/football/784804/borussia-monchengladbach-marcus-thuram-france-lilian/ |access-date=14 November 2020 |publisher=Talksport |date=5 November 2020}}</ref> He debuted on 11 November in a friendly against the Finns, a 2–0 loss at the [[Stade de France]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Finland beat France to ruin Marcus Thuram's debut |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20201111-finland-beat-france-to-ruin-marcus-thuram-s-debut |access-date=14 November 2020 |publisher=France 24 |date=11 November 2020}}</ref> He was called up for the delayed [[UEFA Euro 2020]] in May 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema makes surprise return to the French squad for European Championship after exile for blackmail |url=https://www.france24.com/en/sport/20210518-benzema-makes-surprise-return-to-french-squad-for-euros-after-exile-for-blackmail-scandal |access-date=20 May 2021 |publisher=France 24 |date=18 May 2021}}</ref>

On 14 November 2022, Thuram received a late call-up for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], raising the squad to 26 players.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Marcus-thuram-appele-en-equipe-de-france-pour-la-coupe-du-monde/1364799|title=Marcus Thuram appelé en équipe de France pour la Coupe du monde|trans-title=Marcus Thuram called up to the France team for the World Cup|newspaper=[[L'Équipe]]|language=fr|date=14 November 2022|access-date=14 November 2022}}</ref> In the [[2022 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], he and [[Randal Kolo Muani]] were brought on in place of [[Ousmane Dembélé]] and [[Olivier Giroud]] with France losing 2–0 in the 41st minute. He assisted [[Kylian Mbappé]]'s equalizer to make it 2–2 at the end of regulation time, and was also booked for [[Diving (association football)|diving]] in the penalty area; France lost in a penalty shootout after a 3–3 draw.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McNulty |first1=Phil |title=Argentina 3&ndash;3 France |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63932622 |access-date=18 December 2022 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 December 2022}}</ref> On 7 September, he scored his first international goal in a 2–0 win over [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]] during the [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|Euro 2024 qualifying]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/euro-qualifying/2024/france-2-0-ireland-aurelien-tchouameni-marcus-thuram-goals-extend-les-bleus-perfect-record-in-euro-2_sto9780592/story.shtml |title=France 2-0 Ireland: Aurelien Tchouameni, Marcus Thuram goals extend Les Bleus' perfect record in Euro 2024 qualifying |publisher=Eurosport |date=7 September 2023 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Thuram is the son of the former French international footballer [[Lilian Thuram]], and the older brother of [[Juventus]] and [[France national football team|France]] midfielder [[Khéphren Thuram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/marcus-thuram-17-son-of-barca-hero-lilian-thuram-scored-the-winner-in-a-cup-final-on-saturday-videos/|title=Marcus Thuram (17), son of Barca hero Lilian Thuram, scored the winner in a cup final on Saturday|first=Benjamin|last=Newman|date=30 March 2015|access-date=25 May 2017|publisher=101 Great Goals}}</ref> He was born in the Italian city of [[Parma]] while his father played for the [[Parma Calcio 1913|club]], and was named after Jamaican activist [[Marcus Garvey]].<ref name=bbc>{{cite news |title=Gianluigi Buffon faces Marcus Thuram, son of former team-mate Lilian Thuram |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45239357 |access-date=27 December 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.franceinter.fr/emissions/l-oeil-du-tigre/l-oeil-du-tigre-18-juin-2017|title=L'histoire des premiers noirs dans le sport français|work=France Inter|access-date=23 June 2017|language=fr-FR|trans-title=The history of the first Black people in French sports|last=Philippe|first=Collin|date=2017-08-16}}</ref> Despite his father playing for [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], as a child, he supported [[AC Milan]] and [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fisher |first=Oliver |date=2020-10-20 |title=Monchengladbach star reveals why he supported Milan as a child over Juventus or Inter |url=https://sempremilan.com/monchengladbach-star-reveals-why-he-supported-milan-as-a-child-over-juventus-or-inter |access-date=2026-04-21 |website=SempreMilan |language=en}}</ref> Thuram is of Guadeloupean descent through his father.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lilian Thuram: the legend who came from nothing |url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/12/28/in-celebration-of-lilian-thuram/ |publisher=These Football Times |access-date=28 November 2018 |archive-date=29 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129054402/https://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/12/28/in-celebration-of-lilian-thuram/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

